rry Middlebrooks Jr., James Cobb Jr., Buddy Buie\n|-\n| [[James Arthur]] || rowspan=\"2\" {{n/a|Non-album single}} || \"At My Weakest\" || [[James Arthur]], [[Mark Crew]]\n|-\n| Kara Marni || \"Move\" || Antonia Karamarni, [[Jessica Ashley|Jessica Karpov]], [[The Invisible Men|George Astasio]], [[The Invisible Men|Jason Pebworth]], [[The Invisible Men|Jonathan Shave]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2019 || [[Gryffin]] || ''[[Gravity (Gryffin album)|Gravity]]'' || \"Hurt People\"<br>{{small|(with [[Aloe Blacc]])}} || [[Gryffin|Daniel Griffith]], Corey Saunders, Matthew Holmes, Philip Leigh\n|-\n| The Modern Strangers || ''Visions EP'' || \"Visions\" || Maxwell Davenport, Archibald Davenport, [[The Invisible Men|George Astasio]], [[The Invisible Men|Jason Pebworth]], [[The Invisible Men|Jonathan Shave]]\n|-\n| Moss Kena || {{n/a|Non-album single}} || \"Begging\" || Moss Kena, [[Mark Crew]], Daniel Priddy\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2020 || [[Tom Grennan]] || {{TBA}} || \"This Is The Place\" || [[Tom Grennan]], Elizabeth Blanchard, [[Richard Boardman]], Daniel Boyle, David Straaf\n|-\n| Love Fame Tragedy || ''Five Songs To Briefly Fill The Void'' || \"Multiply\"<br>{{small|(with [[Jack River]])}} || [[Mark Crew]], [[Matthew Murphy]]\n|-\n| [[Cailin Russo]] || ''The Drama'' || \"Sicko\" || [[Cailin Russo]], George Astasio, [[Miranda Cooper]], Jason Pebworth, Jon Shave\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Bastille}}https://bestlaidplansrecords.com/about/<nowiki/>{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Dan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of South African descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:Electropop musicians]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n[[Category:Bastille (band) members]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leeds]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!--See WP:WikiProject Musicians-->\n| name             = Dan Smith\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Dan_Smith_Strand_Fesztival.jpg\n| landscape        = no\n| caption          = Smith performing with [[Bastille (band)|Bastille]] at [[Strand Festival]] in [[Hungary]] in 2019\n| birth_name       = Daniel Campbell Smith\n| Alture           = 1.76\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1986|7|14}}<ref>{{Cite web |title=Bastille's storming success |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/10400588/Bastilles-storming-success.html |accessdate=2015-06-18 |date=25 October 2013 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |last=McCormick |first=Neil}} McCormick says in October 2013 that Smith is 27 years old, and that his birthday is July 14, Bastille Day.</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[London]], [[England]]\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Alternative rock]]|[[electropop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|record producer}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|piano|keyboards|[[melodica]]}}\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]|[[Virgin EMI Records|Virgin EMI]]|[[Capitol Records|Capitol]]|[[Universal Music Group|Universal]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Bastille (band)|Bastille]]|Annie Oakley Hanging|Randalph|[[Madeon]]}}\n| website          = {{URL|bastillebastille.com}}\n}}\n'''Daniel Campbell Smith''' (born 14 July 1986) is an English singer, songwriter and record producer. He is the lead singer, primary songwriter and founder of the British rock band [[Bastille (band)|Bastille]]. The band formed in 2010 and gained mass popularity in 2013 when the song \"[[Pompeii (song)|Pompeii]]\" was released with their album ''[[Bad Blood (Bastille album)|Bad Blood]]''. The band then released their second album, ''[[Wild World (album)|Wild World]]'' in September 2016. In June 2019, the band released their third album ''[[Doom Days]]''.\n\n==Career==\nSmith attended [[King's College School]] and the [[University of Leeds]] in Leeds, West Yorkshire, where he gained a degree in English Language and Literature<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/features/bastilles-dan-smith-the-quiet-man-who-cant-stop-singing-8535042.html|title=Bastille's Dan Smith: The quiet man who can't stop singing|date=15 March 2013|website=independent.co.uk}}</ref> while also writing about film and music for the Leeds student newspaper. A film obsessive from a young age, he originally wanted to be a director or editor until admitting he was \"more of a fan than a filmmaker\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelineofbestfit.com/features/longread/bastilles-dan-smith-the-movie-geek|title=Bastille\u2019s Dan Smith: The Movie Geek|website=thelineofbestfit.com}}</ref>\n\nAt age fifteen, Smith started writing songs on the piano and his laptop in his bedroom, but kept his music secret from his friends and family until he was persuaded by a friend to enter the Leeds Bright Young Things competition in 2007, which he ultimately became a finalist in.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/leeds/content/articles/2006/12/06/music_byt_2007_finalists_feature.shtml|title=Bright Young Things 2007|first=|last=BBC|website=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> His early recordings included \"Alchemy\", \"Words Are Words\", \"Irreverence\", and \"Dictator\". Smith did not achieve mainstream success in his solo career but continued writing songs both alone and with his close friend and roommate Ralph Pelleymounter of the band [[To Kill a King (band)|To Kill a King]]. The two formed a side project called \"Annie Oakley Hanging\" which was described as \"cowboy-like\" by Pelleymounter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sofarsounds.tumblr.com/post/44087449593/sofar-chat-with-ralph-lead-vocalist-of-to-kil|title=Sofar chat with Ralph, lead vocalist of To Kill A King|website=tumblr.com|access-date=17 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151102195910/http://sofarsounds.tumblr.com/post/44087449593/sofar-chat-with-ralph-lead-vocalist-of-to-kil|archive-date=2 November 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter finishing his studies, Smith returned to London, where he continued pursuing his solo career, and eventually formed [[Bastille (band)|Bastille]] with Chris \"Woody\" Wood, Kyle Simmons, and Will Farquarson.<ref>Earmilk.com, [http://earmilk.com/2011/11/10/earmilk-interview-bastille/ Earmilk Interview: BASTILLE]</ref> Bastille has released three albums called ''[[Bad Blood (Bastille album)|Bad Blood]]'', ''[[Wild World (album)|Wild World]]'' and ''[[Doom Days]]'', the latest of which was released June 14 2019.\n\nIn 2014, Dan Smith took part in the [[Band Aid 30|Band Aid]] charity single, \"Do They Know It's Christmas?\".\n\nBEST LAID PLANS is an independent record label based in South London which was founded in 2014 by Dan Smith, Mark Crew, and Dan Priddy to release music that they love.\n\nIn 2015, Smith featured as vocalist for the song \"La Lune,\" produced and written by the French electronic musician [[Madeon]] for Madeon's 2015 album [[Adventure (Madeon album)|Adventure]]. In the same year, Smith co-wrote and provided vocals on \"Better Love\" with [[Foxes (singer)|Foxes]], which was released 4 September 2015.\n\nIn 2017, he participated in the Grenfell Tower charity song, \"[[Bridge over Troubled Water (song)#Artists for Grenfell charity single|Bridge Over Troubled Water]]\".\n\nIn August 2018, [[Bastille (band)|Bastille]] collaborated with American DJ, [[Marshmello]] and released a single entitled \"[[Happier (Marshmello and Bastille song)|Happier]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/8470681/marshmello-bastille-new-song-happier|title=Marshmello and Bastille Bounce Bright On 'Happier': Listen|website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 Brit Awards]], Smith performed a duet with American artist, [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], of her song, \"[[Just Give Me a Reason]]\", as part of her medley performance.\n\nOn 14 June 2019, the band released their third album ''[[Doom Days]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/06/bastilles-doom-days-reveals-a-band-stuck-on-autopilot|title=Bastille\u2019s \u2018Doom Days\u2019 reveals a band stuck on autopilot|website=The Chronicle}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8515953/bastille-dan-smith-doom-days-interview|title=Bastille's Dan Smith Breaks Down Third Album 'Doom Days'|website=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, a cover of the [[REO Speedwagon]] song \"[[Can't Fight This Feeling]]\" sung by Smith was used in the [[John Lewis & Partners]] 2019 [[John Lewis & Partners Christmas advert|Christmas advert]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/listen-bastilles-dan-smith-covering-cant-fight-feeling-john-lewis-christmas-advert-2567822|title=Listen to Bastille's Dan Smith cover of 'Can't Fight This Feeling' for the John Lewis Christmas ad|last=Aubrey|first=Elizabeth|date=2019-11-14|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==Influences==\nSmith is a fan of the TV series ''[[Twin Peaks]]'', and of one of its creators, [[David Lynch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=INUgiN9gfqg|title=Bastille Obsess on David Lynch, Explain They're Not Rock|first=|last=Radio.com|date=6 February 2014|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> The show inspired one of his first recorded songs, \"[[Laura Palmer (Bastille song)|Laura Palmer]]\" and Bastille's first Virgin Records single \"[[Overjoyed (Bastille song)|Overjoyed]]\". Smith has said that his earlier work was influenced by [[Regina Spektor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wonderlandmagazine.com/2012/09/17/new-noise-bastille/|title=NEW NOISE: Bastille|date=17 September 2012|website=Wonderland}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe writes and arranges some of Bastille's songs, apart from remixes and covers, and worked with friend Mark Crew to produce ''[[Bad Blood (Bastille album)|Bad Blood]]'' and ''[[Wild World (album)|Wild World]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wHf5KrNWAoM?t=7m26s|title=Bastille Interview (Part One) - SPGtv|first=|last=The Student Pocket Guide|date=20 March 2013|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> He plays the piano, keyboard, percussion, and [[melodica]]. His original, \"Dan Smith Piano\" was stolen in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/bastilledan/status/14047663686|title=BASTILLE on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=2018-11-28|language=en}}</ref>\nSmith's parents are [[South Africa]]n.<ref>amp.theguardian.com/music/2016/aug/25/dan-smith-bastille-i-sound-like-a-nervous-wreck-who-hates-doing-this</ref>\n\n==Songwriting credits==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \n! Year !! Artist !! Album !! Song !! Co-written with\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2010 || rowspan=\"2\"| [[Gabriella Cilmi]] || rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[Ten (Gabriella Cilmi album)|Ten]]'' || \"Robots\" || [[Gabriella Cilmi]], [[The Invisible Men|George Astasio]], [[The Invisible Men|Jason Pebworth]], [[The Invisible Men|Jonathan Shave]]\n|-\n| \"Sucker for Love\" || [[Gabriella Cilmi]], [[The Invisible Men|George Astasio]], [[The Invisible Men|Jason Pebworth]], [[The Invisible Men|Jonathan Shave]]\n|-\n| [[Olly Murs]] || ''[[Olly Murs (album)|Olly Murs]]'' || \"Love Shine Down\" {{small|(featuring [[Jessie J]])}} || [[Olly Murs|Oliver Murs]], [[Ed Sheeran|Edward Christopher Sheeran]], [[The Invisible Men|George Astasio]], [[The Invisible Men|Jason Pebworth]], [[The Invisible Men|Jonathan Shave]]\n|-\n| 2013 || [[To Kill a King (band)|To Kill a King]] || ''Cannibals with Cutlery'' || \"Choices\" || [[To Kill a King (band)|Ralph Pelleymounter]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2014 || [[Dan Croll]] || ''[[Sweet Disarray]]'' || \"Wanna Know\" || [[Dan Croll|Daniel Croll]], [[The Invisible Men|George Astasio]], [[The Invisible Men|Jason Pebworth]], [[The Invisible Men|Jonathan Shave]]\n|-\n| [[Rag'n'Bone Man]] || ''Wolves EP'' || \"Lay My Body Down\" || [[Rag'n'Bone Man|Rory Graham]], [[Mark Crew]], Daniel Priddy\n|-\n| 201