Traditional Medicine Hospital\n\n==Education==\n* [[Bago University]]\n* [[Basic Education High School No. 1 Bago]]\n*[[Basic Education High School No. 3 Bago]] \n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book | last=Aung-Thwin | first=Michael A. | title=The Mists of R\u0101ma\u00f1\u00f1a: The Legend that was Lower Burma | edition=illustrated | publisher=University of Hawai'i Press | year=2005 | location=Honolulu | isbn=9780824828868}}\n* {{cite book | last=Aung-Thwin | first=Michael A. | title=Myanmar in the Fifteenth Century | publisher=University of Hawai'i Press | year=2017 | location=Honolulu | isbn=978-0-8248-6783-6}}\n* {{cite book | editor=Nyein Maung | title=Shay-haung Myanma Kyauksa-mya [Ancient Burmese Stone Inscriptions] | volume=1\u20135 | language=Burmese | location=Yangon | publisher=Archaeological Department | year=1972\u20131998}}\n* {{cite book | last=Pan Hla | first=Nai | title=[[Razadarit Ayedawbon]] | language=Burmese | year=1968 | edition=8th printing, 2005 | location=Yangon | publisher=Armanthit Sarpay}}\n* {{cite journal | last=[[Arthur Purves Phayre|Phayre]] | first=Major-General Sir Arthur P. | title=The History of Pegu | work=Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal | volume=42 | year=1873 | location=Calcutta | pages=23\u201357, 120\u2013159 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CboIAAAAQAAJ }}\n* {{cite book | last=[[Arthur Purves Phayre|Phayre]] | first=Lt. Gen. Sir Arthur P. | title=History of Burma | year=1883 | edition=1967 | publisher=Susil Gupta | location=London}}\n* {{cite journal | last=Schmidt | first=P.W. | title=Slapat des Ragawan der K\u00f6nigsgeschichte | work=Die \u00e4thiopischen Handschriften der K.K. Hofbibliothek zu Wien | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0A1LAQAAMAAJ | location=Vienna | year=1906 | language=German | volume=151 | publisher=Alfred H\u00f6lder}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category|Bago, Myanmar|Bago}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=vWLRxJEU49EC&pg=PA60&lpg=PA60&dq=Bago+River&source=bl&ots=RE8Cumden-&sig=9HY_znUPbIB0TyuQsK1fisL1_jk&hl=en&ei=_Sd_SvraEN2fjAeS4qHxAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5#v=onepage&q=Bago%20River&f=false International Dictionary of Historic Places: Asia and Oceania]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Donwun]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Capital of Burma|Capital of Hanthawaddy Kingdom]]|years=1369 \u2013 by 31 March 1539}}\n{{s-aft|after=End of Kingdom}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Taungoo|Toungoo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Capital of Burma]]|years=by 31 March 1539 \u2013 30 April 1550}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Inwa|Ava]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=Founded}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Capital of Burma|Capital of Hanthawaddy Kingdom]]|years=June 1550 \u2013 12 March 1552}}\n{{s-aft|after=End of Kingdom}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Taungoo|Toungoo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Capital of Burma]]|years=12 March 1552 \u2013 19 December 1599}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Inwa|Ava]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Inwa|Ava]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Capital of Burma]]|years=14 May 1613 \u2013 25 January 1635}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Inwa|Ava]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=Founded}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Capital of Burma|Capital of Restored Hanthawaddy Kingdom]]|years=November 1740 \u2013 6 May 1757}}\n{{s-aft|after=End of Kingdom}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Bago Region}}\n{{Most populous cities in Myanmar}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Bago (Myanmar)}}\n\n{{Coord|17|20|N|96|29|E|type:city|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Township capitals of Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Bago Region]]\n[[Category:Old Cities of Mon people]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Pegu|the village in Iran|Pegu, Iran}}{{For|the kingdom|Hanthawaddy Pegu}}{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name = Bago<br />\n|settlement_type  =  City\n| native_name = {{lang|my|\u1015\u1032\u1001\u1030\u1038\u1019\u103c\u102d\u102f\u1037}}\n| image_skyline = Bago-Rundblick von Mahazedi Paya (4).JPG\n| image_map = \n| map_caption = \n| pushpin_map = Myanmar\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of Bago, Myanmar\n| coordinates = {{coord|17|20|12|N|96|28|47|E|region:MM|display=inline}}\n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name = {{flag|Myanmar}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Administrative divisions of Myanmar|Division]]\n| subdivision_name1 = {{flag|Bago Region}}\n| established_title = Founded\n| established_date = 1152CE\n| unit_pref = Imperial\n| area_total_km2 = \n| elevation_m = 4\n| elevation_ft = \n| population_total = 491,434\n| population_as_of = 2014\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_metro = \n| population_blank1_title = Ethnicities\n| population_blank1 = [[Bamar]], [[Shan people|Shan]], [[Burmese Chinese]], [[Burmese Indians]], [[Karen people|Kayin]]\n| population_blank2_title = Religions\n| population_blank2 = [[Buddhism]]\n| website = \n| timezone = [[Myanmar Standard Time|MMT]]\n| utc_offset = +6.30\n}}\n\n'''Bago''' (formerly spelt '''Pegu''';<ref>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Pegu |volume=21 |page=58}}</ref> {{MYname|MY={{my|\u1015\u1032\u1001\u1030\u1038\u1019\u103c\u102d\u102f\u1037}}|MLCTS=pai: khu: mrui.}}, {{IPA-my|b\u0259\u0261\u00f3 mjo\u0330|IPA}}; {{lang-mnw|\u1017\u1002\u1031\u102b}}, {{IPA-mnw|h\u0259k\u025c\u0300|}}), formerly known as '''Hanthawaddy''' ({{Lang-my|\u101f\u1036\u101e\u102c\u101d\u1010\u102e }}; {{Lang-mnw|\u101f\u1036\u101e\u102c\u101d\u1010\u1033}} {{transl|mnw|Hongsawatoi}}; {{Lang-pi|italic=yes|Ha\u1e43s\u0101vat\u012b}}; meaning \"She Who Has [[Hamsa (bird)|Sheldrake ]]\"), is a city and the capital of the [[Bago Region]] in [[Myanmar]]. It is located {{convert|91|km|mi}} north-east of [[Yangon]].\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Shwethalyaungbuddhabago.jpg|thumb|left|The 177&nbsp;ft (54&nbsp;m) [[Shwethalyaung Buddha]], constructed in 994 A.D. by King Migadepa]]\n{{see also|Hanthawaddy Kingdom}}\n\nVarious [[Mon language]] [[Burmese chronicles|chronicles]] report widely divergent foundation dates of Bago, ranging from 573 CE to 1152 CE<ref group=note>A version of the 18th century chronicle ''[[Slapat Rajawan]]'' as reported by [[Arthur Purves Phayre|Arthur Phayre]] (Phayre 1873: 32) states that the settlement was founded in 1116 [[Buddhist calendar|Buddhist Era]] (572/573 CE). But another version of the ''Slapat'', used by P.W. Schmidt (Schmidt 1906: 20, 101), states that it was founded on 1st waxing of [[Tabodwe|Mak (Tabodwe)]] 1116 BE ({{circa}} 19 January 573 CE), which it says is equivalent to year 514 of \"the third era\", without specifying what the era specifically was. However, per (Phayre 1873: 39), one of the \"native records\" used by Maj. Lloyd says that Pegu was founded in 514 [[Burmese calendar|Burmese (Myanmar) Era]] (1152/1153 CE). <br/> If the year 514 is indeed the Burmese Era, then the ''Slapat's'' 1st waxing of Tabodwe 514 would be 27 December 1152, equivalent to 1st waxing of Tabodwe 1696 BE (not 1116 BE).</ref> while the ''[[Zabu Kuncha]]'', an early 15th century Burmese administrative treatise, states that Pegu was founded in 1276/77 CE.<ref name=mat-2017-332>Aung-Thwin 2017: 332</ref> The earliest extant evidence of Pegu as a place dates only to the late [[Pagan Kingdom|Pagan period]] (1212 and 1266)<ref group=note>(Aung-Thwin 2005: 59) cites the inscription found at the Min-Nan-Thu village near [[Bagan]], which as shown in (SMK Vol. 3 1983: 28\u201331) was donated by daughter of Theingathu, dated Thursday, 7th waxing of Nanka (Wagaung) 628 ME (8 July 1266), and lists Pegu as Pe-Ku. (Aung-Thwin 2017: 200, 332) updates by saying that the earliest extant inscriptions that mention Pegu date to 1212 and 1266 but does not provide the source of the 1212 inscription. It must be a recent discovery as none of the inscriptions listed in the ''Ancient Burmese Stone Inscriptions'' (SMK Vol. 1 1972: 93\u2013102) for years 573 ME (1211/1212) or 574 ME (1212/1213) shows Pe-Ku or Pegu.</ref> when it was still a small town, not even a provincial capital. After the collapse of the Pagan Empire, Bago became part of the breakaway [[Hanthawaddy Kingdom|Kingdom of Martaban]] by the 1290s.\n\nThe small settlement grew increasingly important in the 14th century as the region became most populous in the Mon-speaking kingdom. In 1369, King [[Binnya U]] made Bago the capital. The city remained the capital until the kingdom's fall in 1538.\n\nDuring the reign of King [[Razadarit]], Bago and [[Ava Kingdom]] were engaged in the [[Forty Years' War]]. The peaceful reign of Queen [[Shin Sawbu]] came to an end when she chose the Buddhist monk [[Dhammazedi]] (1471\u20131492) to succeed her. Under Dhammazedi, Bago became a centre of commerce and [[Theravada]] [[Buddhism]].\n\nIn 1519, [[Ant\u00f3nio Correia (admiral)|Ant\u00f3nio Correia]], then a merchant from the Portuguese ''casados'' settlement at [[Cochin]] landed in Bago, then known to the Portuguese as Pegu, looking for new markets for pepper from Cochin.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lu\u00eds Filipe Tom\u00e1s|url=http://actd.iict.pt/eserv/actd:SEPV096/n096.pdf|title=A viagem de Ant\u00f3nio Correia a Pegu em 1519|publisher=Junta de Investiga\u00e7\u00f5es do Ultramar, [Lisboa]|date=1976|language=portuguese|accessdate=2014-08-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Malekandathil, Pius M C|url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/13205/10/10_chapter%203.pdf|title=ORIGIN AND GROWTH OF LUSO-INDIAN COMMUNITY in Portuguese Cochin and the maritime trade of India, 1500-6663|publisher=Pondicherry University|date=2010-10-26|accessdate=2014-08-05}}|</ref> A year later, [[List of governors of Portuguese India|Portuguese India Governor]] [[Diogo Lopes de Sequeira]] sent an ambassador to Pegu.\n\nAs a major seaport, the city was frequently visited by Europeans, among these, [[Gasparo Balbi]] and [[Ralph Fitch]] in the late 1500s. The Europeans often commented on its magnificence.\n[[File:The king of PEgu recievs an envoy (17th century).jpg|left|thumb|278x278px|The king of Pegu receives an envoy (17th century)]]\nThe Portuguese conquest of Pegu, following the destruction caused by the kings of Tangot and Arrakan in 1599, was described by Manuel de Abreu Mousinho in \"Breve discurso em que se conta a conquista do Reino do Peg\u00fa na India oriental feita pelos portugueses em tempo do vice-rei Aires de Saldanha, sendo capit\u00e3o Salvador Ribeiro de Sousa, chamado Massinga, natural de Guimar\u00e3es, a quem os naturais do Peg\u00fa elegeram por seu rei no ano de 1600\" (Brief narrative telling the conquest of Pegu in eastern India made by the Portuguese in the time of the viceroy Aires de Saldanha, being captain Salvador Ribeiro de Sousa, called Massinga, born in Guimar\u00e3es, elected as their king by the natives in the year 1600), published from 1711 to 1829 with \"Peregrina\u00e7am\" of Fern\u00e3o Mendes Pinto.\n\nThe capital was looted by the viceroy of [[Toungoo]], [[Minye Thihathu II of Toungoo]], and then burned by the viceroy of [[Rakhine State|Arakin]] during the [[Burmese\u2013Siamese War (1594\u20131605)]]. [[Anaukpetlun]] wanted to rebuild Hongsawadi, which had been deserted since [[Nanda Bayin]] had abandoned it.  He was only able to build a temporary palace, however.<ref name=Damrong>Rajanubhab, D., 2001, Our Wars With the Burmese, Bangkok: White Lotus Co. Ltd., {{ISBN|9747534584}}</ref>{{rp|151\u2013162,191}}\n\nThe Burmese capital relocated to [[Inwa|Ava]] in 1634. In 1740, the Mon revolted and founded the [[Restored Hanthawaddy Kingdom]]. However, a [[Bamar people|Bamar]] king, [[Alaungpaya]], captured the city in May 1757.\n\nBago was rebuilt by King [[Bodawpaya]] (r. 1782-1819), but by then the river had shifted course, cutting the city off from the sea. It never regained its previous importance. After the [[Second Anglo-Burmese War]], the [[British Empire|British]] annexed Bago in 1852. In 1862, the province of [[British rule in Burma|British Burma]] was formed, and the capital moved to [[Yangon]]. The substantial differences between the colloquial and literary pronunciations, as with Burmese words, was a reason of the British corruption \"Pegu\".\n\nIn 1911, Hanthawaddy was described as a district in the [[Bago Region|Bago]] (or ''Pegu'') division of [[Lower Burma]]. It lay in the home district of [[Yangon]], from which the town was detached to make a separate district in 1880. It had an area of {{convert|3023|sqmi|km2}}, with a population of 48,411 in 1901, showing an increase of 22% in the past decade. Hanthawaddy and [[Hinthada]] were the two most densely populated districts in the province.\n\nHanthawaddy, as it was constituted in 1911, consisted of a vast plain stretching up from the sea between the mouth of the [[Irrawaddy River]] and the [[Pegu Range]]. Except the tract of land lying between the Pegu Range on the east and the [[Yangon River]], the country was intersected by numerous [[Creek (tidal)|tidal creek]]s, many of which were navigable by large boats and some by steamers. The headquarters of the district was in Rangoon, which was also the sub-divisional headquarters. The second sub-division had its headquarters at [[Insein Township|Insein]], where there were large railway works. Cultivation was almost wholly confined to rice, but there were many vegetable and fruit gardens.\n\nToday, Hanthawaddy is one of the wards of Bago city.\n\n==Climate==\n{{Weather box\n| location = Bago, Myanmar (1981\u20132010)\n| single line  = Y\n| metric first = Y\n| Jan high C = 31.6\n| Feb high C = 34.0\n| Mar high C = 36.2\n| Apr high C = 38.1\n| May high C = 34.3\n| Jun high C = 30.1\n| Jul high C = 29.7\n| Aug high C = 29.6\n| Sep high C = 30.8\n| Oct high C = 30.7\n| Nov high C = 32.2\n| Dec high C = 31.0\n| year high C = 32.4\n| Jan low C = 15.8\n| Feb low C = 17.2\n| Mar low C = 20.2\n| Apr low C = 23.1\n| May low C = 23.4\n| Jun low C = 22.7\n| Jul low C = 22.7\n| Aug low C = 22.6\n| Sep low C = 22.8\n| Oct low C = 23.0\n| Nov low C = 20.9\n| Dec low C = 16.9\n| year low C = 20.9\n| rain colour = green\n| Jan rain mm = 1.3\n| Feb rain mm = 2.7\n| Mar rain mm = 13.5\n| Apr rain mm = 44.1\n| May rain mm = 333.9\n| Ju