y Arsenal Football Academy who preferred two other prospects at his position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/david-beckham-son-brooklyn-football-2015-9|title=David Beckham's oldest son no longer wants to play soccer, and the reason why broke his dad's heart|first=Cork|last=Gaines|website=Business Insider}}</ref>\n\nHe started modelling in 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eonline.com/news/526717/brooklyn-beckham-makes-modeling-debut-on-man-about-town-magazine-see-the-pics|title=Brooklyn Beckham Makes Modeling Debut on Man About Town Magazin|date=31 March 2014|website=E! Online}}</ref> and has appeared in editorials and covers for ''[[Vogue China]]'', ''[[Vogue (British magazine)|Miss Vogue]]'', ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'', ''[[L'Uomo Vogue]]'', ''[[The New York Times|T:The New York Times Style Magazine]]'', and ''[[Dazed]] Korea''. He has been photographed by [[Bruce Weber (photographer)|Bruce Weber]], [[Terry Richardson]], Daniel Jackson, and [[Alasdair McLellan]]. Beckham himself photographed a campaign for [[Burberry]] BRIT, starring models Ben Rees, Carvell Conduah, Eliza Thomas, Liv Mason Pearson, and Maddie Demaine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fashionista.com/2016/07/brooklyn-beckham-burberry-fragrance|title=BROOKLYN BECKHAM'S FRAGRANCE CAMPAIGN FOR BURBERRY IS HERE|work=Fashionista}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://models.com/work/burberry-prorsum-brit-fragrance|title=Brit Fragrance 2016 (Burberry)|website=MODELS.com}}</ref>\n\nHe is a part of a modelling trend where children of famous people and models with large social media presence are successful.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://models.com/oftheminute/?p=80347|title=Moments of the Year: 6. Celebrity Kin|work=models.com}}</ref> He has a strong following of Chinese fans; he has been the face of [[Huawei]] Honor 8 Android phones alongside [[Scarlett Johansson]], [[Karlie Kloss]], and [[Henry Cavill]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-37106220|title=Why is Brooklyn Beckham selling phones?|first=Rhiannon|last=Williams|date=17 August 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.com|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBeckham previously dated American actress [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]] and French model-singer [[Sonia Ben Ammar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/chloe-grace-moretz-confirms-shes-dating-brooklyn-beckham/|title=WATCH: Chlo&#235; Grace Moretz Confirms She's Dating Brooklyn Beckham: 'Yes, We're in a Relationship'|website=PEOPLE.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/fashion/people/everything-you-need-to-know-about-brooklyn-beckhams-girlfriend-s/|title=Everything you need to know about Brooklyn Beckham's 'girlfriend' Sonia Ben Ammar|first1=Emma|last1=Spedding|first2=Bibby|last2=Sowray|date=14 March 2016|newspaper=Telegraph}}</ref> He attended the [[2016 Democratic National Convention]] with Moretz in support of [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/celebrities/news/a38186/chloe-grace-moretz-brooklyn-beckham-dnc/|title=Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz Had Best Date Ever at the Democratic National Convention|first=Kristina|last=Rodulfo|date=29 July 2016|website=ELLE}}</ref>\nHe began dating American actress [[Nicola  Peltz]] since November 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beckham, Brooklyn}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English male models]]\n[[Category:English photographers]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Parsons School of Design alumni]]\n", "name_user": "PaulaMorgan404", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brooklyn_Beckham"}
{"title_page": "Joe Grim", "text_new": "{{short description|American boxer}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| image = Joe Grim 1904.jpg\n| name = Joe Grim\n| nationality = American\n| realname = Saverio Giannone\n| nickname = The Iron Man\n| weight = [[Middleweight]]<br>[[Welterweight]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1881|03|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Avellino]], [[Campania]], [[Italy]]\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|1939|01|01|1881|03|16}}\n|death_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]\n| home = \n| reach = \n| height = 5\u2032 7\u2033 (1.7m)\n| style = Orthodox\n| total = 152\n| wins = 24\n| KO = 10\n| losses = 104\n| draws = 22\n| no contests = 2\n}}'''Joe Grim''' (born '''Saverio Giannone'''; March 16, 1881 \u2013 January 1, 1939) was an [[Italian American]] [[Boxing|boxer]] of the early 20th century.\n\nGrim was born in [[Avellino]], [[Campania]], and he and his family emigrated to the [[United States]] when he was ten. As a boxer, he engaged in over 150 professional bouts; some sources put the figure at 300 to 500.<ref name=\"iron man\">{{cite news|url=http://www.onmilwaukee.com/sports/articles/joegrim.html|title=\"Iron Man\" Joe Grim found fame with a thick skull|publisher=OnMilwaukee.com|date=January 7, 2013|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"ironclad\">{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1085005/1/index.htm|title=The Ironclad Punching Bag|publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date= June 21, 1971|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"legendary\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=861&dat=19440512&id=dvJHAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kYAMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2804,1974348|title=Grim Became Legendary As The Man Nobody Could Knock Out|publisher=The Victoria Advocate|date=May 12, 1944|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref> Despite losing the majority of his fights, Grim became a popular fighter; his principal claim to fame was his ability to absorb heavy punishment without being [[Knockout|knocked out]], for which he was nicknamed \"The Iron Man\" and \"The Human Punching Bag\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1928&dat=19240409&id=urkgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=emkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2489,623852|title=Joe Grim Was World Champion Door-Mat|publisher=The Lewiston Daily Sun|date=April 9, 1924|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"defi\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=336&dat=19031102&id=I50wAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VEoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3045,6554562|title=Joe Grim Issues Defi To Jeffries|publisher=[[The Deseret News]]|date=November 2, 1903|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19041030&id=IAAbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7UgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5958,6378178|title=Joe Grim Coming|publisher=[[The Pittsburgh Press]]|date=October 30, 1904|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"barred\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19040223&id=YRYbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CkkEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3594,3023230|title=Joe Grim Should Be Barred From Ring|publisher=[[The Pittsburgh Press]]|date=February 23, 1904|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref> Typically, at the end of a bout, he would go to the ropes and shout \"I am Joe Grim. I fear no man on earth.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1084719/4/index.htm|title=No Requiem For A Heavyweight|publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=April 5, 1971|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref> In 1930 he was described in ''[[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]]'' as \"the greatest physical freak the prize ring ever knew... Grim offered his body as a target to fighters who outweighed him by many pounds. He has the strangest claim to glory that an athlete ever made.\"<ref name=\"iron man\"/> [[Robert W. Edgren]] opined that \"knocking the Iron Man down with fists is a waste of time and effort, for he keeps getting up. To drop Grim for a long count, a boxer \u2013 if permitted \u2013 should use a crowbar or a baseball bat.\"<ref name=\"ironclad\"/>\n\nIn 1903 Grim took on former heavyweight champion [[Bob Fitzsimmons]]. Grim \"took a battering... that would have killed an ordinary man\" and was knocked down repeatedly, but rose to his feet every time and lasted the distance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=37&dat=19031024&id=HwAIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9zUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2275,1041090|title=Grim Stays the Limit with Fitz|publisher=St. John Daily Sun|date=October 24, 1903|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref> Fitzsimmons called Grim \"the hardest proposition to knock out that I have ever met\" and thought him \"insensible to physical pain.\"<ref name=\"defi\"/> Two years later Grim faced future heavyweight champion [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]]. Johnson dominated the six-round fight and by one estimate scored seventeen knockdowns, but Grim again made it to the final bell. Between rounds Johnson remarked to his cornermen: \"he ain't human.\"<ref>{{cite book | author=Ward, Geoffrey C.| title=Unforgiveable Blackness: The Rise and Fall of Jack Johnson| publisher=Random House| year=2005| isbn=978-0-7126-0977-7| pages=74\u201375}}</ref> Afterwards he said: \"I just don't believe that man is made of flesh and blood.\"<ref name=\"casey\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxing.com/joe_grim_how_to_take_it_and_then_some.html|title=Joe Grim: How to Take It and Then Some|publisher=Boxing.com|author=Mike Casey|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref>\n\nHis reputation as a man who could not be knocked out attracted numerous other high profile opponents for Grim, among them [[Barbados Joe Walcott]], [[Jack Blackburn]], [[Joe Gans]], [[Dixie Kid]], [[Philadelphia Jack O'Brien]], [[Battling Levinsky]], and [[Peter Maher (boxer)|Peter Maher]], all of whom were unable to stop him, despite many administering heavy beatings.<ref name=\"legendary\"/> Gans gave him a \"severe pounding\" and knocked him down in most rounds.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=336&dat=19031020&id=GJ0wAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VEoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2232,5091199|title=Grim Stayed Again|publisher=The Deseret News|date=October 20, 1903|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref> The amount of punishment sustained by Grim during his fights led to calls for him to be banned from boxing.<ref name=\"barred\"/> Though Grim did not win many bouts, he was credited with a newspaper decision over former welterweight champion [[Matty Matthews]] in 1904.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=QDEWnZBrHwAC&dat=19040417&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|title=Grim Beat Matty Matthews|publisher=Philadelphia Record|date=April 17, 1904|accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref> He tried unsuccessfully to secure a fight with reigning heavyweight champion [[James J. Jeffries]].<ref name=\"defi\"/> His run came to an end when he was knocked out by [[Sailor Burke]] in 1906. Four years later, he was knocked out by [[Sam McVea]] in [[Paris]].<ref name=\"casey\"/>\nBut the biggest headline on Jan. 1, 1937, highlighted a tradition that never seems to go out of style - a mob hit in South Philly. Mob boss Pius Lanzetti was blasted with a sawed-off shotgun while drinking coffee in a neighborhood luncheonette at s.8th below Fitzwater. The owner of the cafe Joe Grimm fought world heavyweight champion Jack Johnson in a six-round no-decision match on July 24, 1905. He was known as the human punching bag no one could knock him out. He died in 1939 at Byberry lost in all the punches to his head.\n\nGrim began to suffer mental health issues and was admitted to a [[Sanatorium|sanitarium]] in 1913, before being released in 1916.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1915&dat=19160517&id=fP0gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=r3UFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1522,2062992|title=Old Joe Grim is Now Leading Simple Life|publisher=The Day|date=May 17, 1916|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref> He promoted fights in Philadelphia and worked as a foreman in a shipyard in New York.<ref name=\"casey\"/> In later life he was committed to the [[Philadelphia State Hospital at Byberry|Philadelphia Hospital for Mental Diseases]], where he died in 1939.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{boxrec|id=10815}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grim, Joe}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n[[Category:American boxers of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Italian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Middleweight boxers]]\n[[Category:People from Avellino]]\n[[Category:Welterweight boxers]]\n[[Category:American male boxers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American boxer}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| image = Joe Grim 1904.jpg\n| name = Joe Grim\n| nationality = American\n| realname = Saverio Giannone\n| nickname = The Iron Man\n| weight = [[Middleweight]]<br>[[Welterweight]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1881|03|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Avellino]], [[Campania]], [[Italy]]\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|1939|01|01|1881|03|16}}\n|death_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]\n| home = \n| reach = \n| height = 5\u2032 7\u2033 (1.7m)\n| style = Orthodox\n| total = 152\n| wins = 24\n| KO = 10\n| losses = 104\n| draws = 22\n| no contests = 2\n}}'''Joe Grim''' (born '''Saverio Giannone'''; March 16, 1881 \u2013 January 1, 1939) was an [[Italian American]] [[Boxing|boxer]] of the early 20th century.\n\nGrim was born in [[Avellino]], [[Campania]], and he and his family emigrated to the [[United States]] when he was ten. As a boxer, he engaged in over 150 professional bouts; some sources put the figure at 300 to 500.<ref name=\"iron man\">{{cite news|url=http://www.onmilwaukee.com/sports/articles/joegrim.html|title=\"Iron Man\" Joe Grim found fame with a thick skull|publisher=OnMilwaukee.com|date=January 7, 2013|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"ironclad\">{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1085005/1/index.htm|title=The Ironclad Punching Bag|publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date= June 21, 1971|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"legendary\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=861&dat=19440512&id=dvJHAAAAIBAJ&sjid=kYAMAAAAIBAJ&pg=2804,1974348|title=Grim Became Legendary As The Man Nobody Could Knock Out|publisher=The Victoria Advocate|date=May 12, 1944|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref> Despite losing the majority of his fights, Grim became a popular fighter; his principal claim to fame was his ability to absorb heavy punishment without being [[Knockout|knocked out]], for which he was nicknamed \"The Iron Man\" and \"The Human Punching Bag\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1928&dat=19240409&id=urkgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=emkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2489,623852|title=Joe Grim Was World Champion Door-Mat|publisher=The Lewiston Daily Sun|date=April 9, 1924|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"defi\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=336&dat=19031102&id=I50wAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VEoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3045,6554562|title=Joe Grim Issues Defi To Jeffries|publisher=[[The Deseret News]]|date=November 2, 1903|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19041030&id=IAAbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7UgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5958,6378178|title=Joe Grim Coming|publisher=[[The Pittsburgh Press]]|date=October 30, 1904|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"barred\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19040223&id=YRYbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CkkEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3594,3023230|title=Joe Grim Should Be Barred From Ring|publisher=[[The Pittsburgh Press]]|date=February 23, 1904|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref> Typically, at the end of a bout, he would go to the ropes and shout \"I am Joe Grim. I fear no man on earth.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1084719/4/index.htm|title=No Requiem For A Heavyweight|publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=April 5, 1971|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref> In 1930 he was described in ''[[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]]'' as \"the greatest physical freak the prize ring ever knew... Grim offered his body as a target to fighters who outweighed him by many pounds. He has the strangest claim to glory that an athlete ever made.\"<ref name=\"iron man\"/> [[Robert W. Edgren]] opined that \"knocking the Iron Man down with fists is a waste of time and effort, for he keeps getting up. To drop Grim for a long count, a boxer \u2013 if permitted \u2013 should use a crowbar or a baseball bat.\"<ref name=\"ironclad\"/>\n\nIn 1903 Grim took on former heavyweight champion [[Bob Fitzsimmons]]. Grim \"took a battering... that would have killed an ordinary man\" and was knocked down repeatedly, but rose to his feet every time and lasted the distance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=37&dat=19031024&id=HwAIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9zUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2275,1041090|title=Grim Stays the Limit with Fitz|publisher=St. John Daily Sun|date=October 24, 1903|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref> Fitzsimmons called Grim \"the hardest proposition to knock out that I have ever met\" and thought him \"insensible to physical pain.\"<ref name=\"defi\"/> Two years later Grim faced future heavyweight champion [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]]. Johnson dominated the six-round fight and by one estimate scored seventeen knockdowns, but Grim again made it to the final bell. Between rounds Johnson remarked to his cornermen: \"he ain't human.\"<ref>{{cite book | author=Ward, Geoffrey C.| title=Unforgiveable Blackness: The Rise and Fall of Jack Johnson| publisher=Random House| year=2005| isbn=978-0-7126-0977-7| pages=74\u201375}}</ref> Afterwards he said: \"I just don't believe that man is made of flesh and blood.\"<ref name=\"casey\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxing.com/joe_grim_how_to_take_it_and_then_some.html|title=Joe Grim: How to Take It and Then Some|publisher=Boxing.com|author=Mike Casey|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref>\n\nHis reputation as a man who could not be knocked out attracted numerous other high profile opponents for Grim, among them [[Barbados Joe Walcott]], [[Jack Blackburn]], [[Joe Gans]], [[Dixie Kid]], [[Philadelphia Jack O'Brien]], [[Battling Levinsky]], and [[Peter Maher (boxer)|Peter Maher]], all of whom were unable to stop him, despite many administering heavy beatings.<ref name=\"legendary\"/> Gans gave him a \"severe pounding\" and knocked him down in most rounds.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=336&dat=19031020&id=GJ0wAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VEoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2232,5091199|title=Grim Stayed Again|publisher=The Deseret News|date=October 20, 1903|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref> The amount of punishment sustained by Grim during his fights led to calls for him to be banned from boxing.<ref name=\"barred\"/> Though Grim did not win many bouts, he was credited with a newspaper decision over former welterweight champion [[Matty Matthews]] in 1904.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=QDEWnZBrHwAC&dat=19040417&printsec=frontpage&hl=en|title=Grim Beat Matty Matthews|publisher=Philadelphia Record|date=April 17, 1904|accessdate=2014-02-02}}</ref> He tried unsuccessfully to secure a fight with reigning heavyweight champion [[James J. Jeffries]].<ref name=\"defi\"/> His run came to an end when he was knocked out by [[Sailor Burke]] in 1906. Four years later, he was knocked out by [[Sam McVea]] in [[Paris]].<ref name=\"casey\"/>\n\nGrim began to suffer mental health issues and was admitted to a [[Sanatorium|sanitarium]] in 1913, before being released in 1916.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1915&dat=19160517&id=fP0gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=r3UFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1522,2062992|title=Old Joe Grim is Now Leading Simple Life|publisher=The Day|date=May 17, 1916|accessdate=2014-01-30}}</ref> He promoted fights in Philadelphia and worked as a foreman in a shipyard in New York.<ref name=\"casey\"/> In later life he was committed to the [[Philadelphia State Hospital at Byberry|Philadelphia Hospital for Mental Diseases]], where he died in 1939.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{boxrec|id=10815}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grim, Joe}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1939 deaths]]\n[[Category:American boxers of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Italian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Middleweight boxers]]\n[[Category:People from Avellino]]\n[[Category:Welterweight boxers]]\n[[Category:American male boxers]]\n", "name_user": "Mr beamiss", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Grim"}
